##Will the global supply chain shut down? | CAIJING special report

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Although the outbreak affected the processing and production of parts and components in some manufacturing industries, resulting in production disruptions by some tncs, it did not have a measurable long-term impact on the supply chain. China's 30-year-old supply chain can not be completely replaced in the short term

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The fragility of the supply chain has led many European and American companies to consider the possibility of shifting production. Photo / Xinhua

Wen | CAIJING reporters, Cai Tingyi, Wang Xiaoxia, Jiang Yunzhang, Washington correspondent, Jin Yan

Editor | Wang Yanchun

Two weeks ago, the Guoxuan battery in Qingdao, Shandong Province, went back to work in stages, but the current rate is only 50 per cent due to a shortage of raw materials.

Unlike Guoxuan batteries so smooth, Zhejiang Jiaxing Dama Yuhua Textile Company because of the epidemic "raw materials can not enter, products can not go out" , still can not open. Its home town of Dama, famous for its textiles, had 95 per cent of its businesses closed as of February 24. The doors are locked. There's not a lot of traffic.

It was no fluke that Guoxuan was able to resume work. Wang Weidong, chairman of the company, pointed out to a reporter from CAIJING that Guoxuan had set up a leading group to fight the epidemic as soon as the epidemic occurred, in addition, enterprises are required to take body temperature three times a day and issue epidemic prevention materials such as regular disinfection of factories, ventilation and disinfection of dormitories, and masks.

He introduced that at present, the main constraints due to insufficient raw material supply, production capacity can not be fully restored, enterprises had to make contingency arrangements based on their own raw material supply, production orders and other circumstances. Government departments have also provided green channels for the resumption of production and work, with orders partially unaffected by the outbreak.

Sunzoom Household, a hangzhou-based supplier of furniture and sanitary appliances, has been certified by Hilton, an American hotel chain. While rescheduling production and delivery times, Sunzoom Household has already felt the foot-dragging of some customers, so on Alibaba's website, in large English letters, it reads, "the factory is back in operation. Let's talk business. ". CEO Xu Chaoyang of the company pointed out to "CAIJING" reporter, because of the epidemic, some customers comprehensive consideration of costs and other issues, the transfer of some orders to the Southeast Asia region and other situations do exist.

The COVID-19, which started in Wuhan, spread overseas in just a few weeks, challenging not only global health care but also the global economy. As the outbreak spread through Japan, South Korea, Italy and Iran, investor confidence began to darken. Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 2,000 points on Feb. 2426. The Oxford Institute predicts that the impact of the NCP epidemic will reduce global economic growth by 0.2 percentage points in 2020 to 2.3 per cent a year. The double negative impact on the supply and demand of the global economy is of particular concern.

China, Japan, South Korea and Vietnam are important parts of the global manufacturing chain. In 2018, Japan, South Korea and Vietnam accounted for 7.11 percent, 3.11 percent and 0.28 percent of the world's total manufacturing value added, according to the World Bank. If China is included, the four countries account for nearly 40 per cent of world manufacturing value added. The current crisis in the global manufacturing supply chain is spreading as the new crown pneumonia epidemic continues to spread.

More importantly, as the "factory of the world" , China's supply chain is globally embedded, and the impact of the epidemic on China's economy and enterprises has gradually spread to other parts of the world, such as the electronics industry and the automobile industry, even Games, consumer goods and so on. Hyundai suspended several assembly plants in South Korea in early February because of a shortage of parts; Nissan suspended production at its Kyushu Plant for the same reason; and Apple said it was affected by the COVID-19 outbreak, the supply of chips made in China has been hampered and is not expected to meet sales targets for the quarter, while Nintendo's Switch, a hot seller on the other side of the ocean, is facing a global shortage of parts.

In fact, the long-term stability of China's manufacturing supply chain system has also aroused concern under the impact of the sino-us trade war and the COVID-19 epidemic, and some enterprises have begun to reflect on the defects of the manufacturing supply chain arrangements. While it is difficult to predict how the COVID-19 outbreak will affect the geometry of the supply chain, some companies have begun to adjust their strategies, including building multiple supplier networks in different countries. Shorten the supply chain, make communication easier, rearrange and calculate supply and logistics, optimize inventory, and so on.

But many companies are also seeing a silver lining. Under the impact of new crown pneumonia on manufacturing supply chain, enterprises realize the weakness and blind spot of their own supply chain in planning and management. From supply chain in series to in parallel, from flexible chain to flexible chain, enterprises hope to perfect the supply system of manufacturing industry in order to deal with the possible future natural disasters, political unrest and many other Black Swan or gray rhino events.

The status and market of made in China

Apple Inc. (AAPL) issued a financial warning on Feb. 18, saying it was slower than expected to resume production at its contract factories in China because of the outbreak, as a result, quarterly revenue through the end of March may fall short of its target of $63 billion to $67 billion. Shares of apple fell as much as 2% on the news, sending shares of other Asian parts suppliers lower.

Apple's warning followed a twitter announcement by the Japanese Gaming Company Nintendo on Feb. 6 that sales of the new Switch would be delayed because of an outbreak, and a follow up by the U.S. toy company Mga, the outbreak has already affected Christmas toy shipments, the current situation is "very frustrating. ".

China now accounts for 80% of global toy production. Take Mga, an American toy company. The 50 domestic manufacturers it contracts with typically start making fall and Christmas orders after the Lunar New Year, but the outbreak has delayed factory restarts, said Laruns, the company's president, "Christmas 2020 is December 25, and you can't put it off. "

As the COVID-19 epidemic spread, factories and workers across China cooperated in implementing measures to prevent the disease. Some delayed returning to work, while others lacked production capacity, causing varying degrees of impact on the global manufacturing supply chain, many industries are facing a shutdown or chain break, especially electronics and auto manufacturing. Traditional manufacturers such as apparel, footwear and toys are also worried about supply shortages in the second half of the year because of delays in starting factories or the inability of production lines to fully recover.

According to statistics, China is the only country in the world that has all the industrial categories in the United Nations industrial classification. Among more than 500 major industrial products in the world, China has the world's largest output of more than 220 industrial products.

China's dependence on the global economy has declined since 2003, but the global economy's dependence on China has increased, according to a 2019 China and the world report by Mccon. China became the world's largest exporter in 2009 and the largest trader of goods in 2013, accounting for 11.4 percent of global trade in goods in 2017, up from 1.9 percent in 2000, the report said. China is also the largest exporter to 33 countries and the largest importer to 65 countries. The report estimates that China contributes 35% to global manufacturing, with components accounting for 35% to 50% of foreign-branded mobile phones, 60% to 80% of agricultural machinery, and 60% to 75% of electronic cars.

It is not just manufacturing. According to the World Bank, China led a 31 percent increase in global household consumption between 2010 and 2017. It is also the world's largest market for cars, mobile phones, luxury goods and alcohol, accounting for 30 percent of global consumption. The outbreak is expected to cut about $40 billion in revenue from the global luxury goods market, with UK trenchcoat brand Burberry, US leather Coach and Ralph Lauren all warning about the threat.

The sudden outbreak of the disease at home and abroad for the first time in the face of both supply and demand gap challenges. American Chamber of Commerce Shanghai Branch February 11-14 for 109 parents of the Delta business survey, 48% of the enterprises surveyed by the global business has been affected by the epidemic. Of those, 35 percent said the most important thing to do now was to allow factories to resume work, and 78 percent said they did not have enough workers to restore full capacity, forty-one percent of businesses cited job losses as their biggest problem in the next two to four weeks. In addition, 58 per cent of companies are beginning to worry that demand will be below normal in the coming months.

According to the latest survey released by the European Chamber of Commerce on February 27th, 90% of its members said they were moderately or highly affected by the outbreak, while nearly half said they expected a double-digit drop in business revenues, 25% said revenue would fall by more than 20% .

Will the "Manufacturing Center" shut down

Businesses like Dun & Bradstreet compare specific injuries that could be caused by an outbreak from the country's endemic areas and industries, according to a Feb. 11 report by Dun & Bradstreet, the main sectors affected by the COVID-19 epidemic were services, wholesale and manufacturing, with 65 per cent of the related businesses located in the affected areas.

'The supply gap for raw materials and components is an urgent problem for manufacturers outside China, ' Zero Chou, A SINGAPORE-BASED AC trade consultancy, told Caijing. 'logistics is the second issue. ' "Some found materials, but the aircraft embargo. ".

The lack of a small screw or spring in a tightly divided supply chain can prevent the entire product from being made.

For example, a 1 yuan beauty product container needs a plastic bottle body, a spring and a steel ball to form a pressure head. Because empty bottles take up space, beauty product manufacturers do not usually reserve stock, but are now affected by the epidemic, the global beauty industry faces the dilemma of not being able to buy empty bottles and not being able to ship them. Some taiwan-based workers considering placing orders with South Korea have found that Korean manufacturers are also based in China.

The textile industry is also worried about supply-chain gaps. Aqua Regia, general manager of Wuyang Textile, pointed out to the CAIJING reporter that the supporting external coordination units, such as casting, electroplating, blackening treatment, heat treatment and other industries resume work more slowly, affecting the entire production supply chain. He predicted the impact could last until april-may. "I don't think we can see the first quarter data. I'm going to assume the worst, have three months of liquidity to tide me over, and the textile industry is still going to be hit hard. "

'industries are rushing to find new suppliers, ' U.S. supply chain consulting firm Sourcify's Nathan Resnick told Caijing.

According to the Guotai Junan Securities, during the outbreak phase, short-term supply chain risks will be concentrated in automotive and mechanical equipment (parts) , optical and electronic equipment (List of semiconductor materials) and chemical products. But Hua Changchun, chief economist at Guotai Junan Securities, explained to Caijing that the industrial chain is a question of upstream and downstream demand, and the supply chain mainly refers to whether the same industry has enough parts. He explained that one of the reasons the outbreak disrupted global supply chains was that China was a major supplier of intermediate goods. According to the COMTRADE database, China's exports of intermediate goods to 64 countries account for more than 10 percent of local exports, including major economies around the world.

Wuttke, president of the European Chamber of Commerce, told Caijing that the longer the supply chain, the more problems companies will have. In the case of auto manufacturing, even if one of the parts plants starts to function smoothly, the assembly line eventually faces failure when other important parts are delayed.

In the case of electronics manufacturing, in addition to capacity cuts at factories, a shortage of core materials also affects the assembly of the final product. The production of rare earths for televisions, watches, and car glass is threatened by disruptions in electronics manufacturing as truck drivers refuse to enter or leave the affected areas and rare earths are in short supply.

Even if the supply of raw materials can be resolved, epidemic prevention measures within the enterprise are another challenge. Cell Phone sensor suppliers told Caijing that the spread of the disease has caused factories to be able to restore only 40% of their capacity, and other parts factories are likely to do the same. The main reason is that in addition to the 14-day quarantine required for workers returning to the factory, the factory now requires workers to be separated by 2 meters. If the outbreak can be successfully controlled, production capacity will be fully restored as soon as April.

Foxconn, which assembles electronics such as iphones, global desktop computers and laptops, began trial production of masks in Longhua, Guangdong Province, on February 5 in an effort to get back to work, with the aim of producing 2M masks a day by the end of February. Foxconn's Taiwanese parent, Hon Hai precision, said in a Feb. 20 announcement that it was cautious about returning to work and that the outbreak would have a negative impact on revenue for the year. FOXCONN's Zhengzhou and Shenzhen plants have been hit hard and are slowly returning to work, according to reports.

According to the Guotai Junan Securities, the situation will be better at the end of February except in Hubei, which is expected to be up by the end of March. "The impact of the outbreak on enterprises will not be very big. For example, as long as the telecommunications industry resumes work, I believe it will be working overtime, with no rest for machinery and equipment, and personnel can work three shifts. As long as there is no recurrence of the outbreak after the resumption of work, we can catch up with the supply chain soon, " Hua stressed, "Overall, I think the short-term risks are manageable, because at the moment it looks like the overall data for the epidemic has improved significantly except in Hubei, which is confident that it will continue to improve at the current pace. "

Saving fragile supply chains

The attraction of the huge domestic market and the complete industrial chain, along with the outbreak, have become the focus of attention in the 2020 presidential primary election.

Democratic candidate Warren said the United States should find ways to minimize the damage caused by the outbreak to the supply chain, and the U.S. government should help U.S. manufacturers find alternative parts suppliers, at the same time to help exporters find new customers.

Wuttke also pointed out that as a result of the outbreak, companies around the world are hoping to find a complete replacement for Chinese production capacity. The previous trade war between the United States and China did make some companies rethink their dependence on China, the COVID-19 has exacerbated the problem.

The fragility of the supply chain has led many European and American companies to consider the possibility of shifting production. The above-mentioned Sensor Manufacturers pointed out that the unexpected interruption of the manufacturing of this epidemic has caused a serious psychological impact on enterprises. In order to avoid the risk, all foreign cadres will not be required to travel to the epidemic area for the time being, next, "component manufacturers of European and American products will have to consider moving out of China to spread risk... the demand from customers behind has become huge pressure" .

Xu Qiyuan, a researcher at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, told Caijing that China's inability to deliver intermediate goods for export has indeed caused disruptions in production processes in other countries. If the outbreak continues, the global supply chain shock could unfold along two main lines:

One thread is the supply chain crisis in emerging markets and developing countries, where dependence on Chinese intermediate goods is generally high, but the corresponding industrial integration is low and the damage is relatively limited.

The other is that supply chain shocks between Europe, the United States and Japan spread, amplification, some of the higher integration of supply chains will be destroyed, the global economy will fall into a gray rhinoceros-like impact.

However, the "back-up" of global industrial clusters can not be accomplished overnight.

As trade disputes between the United States and China intensified, many companies rushed to build new supply chains in Southeast Asian countries, but they quickly discovered that nowhere offered a more complete solution than in China.

Mantin, a supply chain expert in Luxembourg, told Caijing that the challenges posed by the outbreak reflect the vulnerability of supply chains due to lack of transparency, and the impact has triggered discussions about the importance of alternative supply chains, but the problem can not be solved with alternative suppliers in the same country, and as the epidemic heats up globally, it is no longer an individual country's problem.

While multinational companies need to consider the market and risk aversion, Hua believes that some multinational companies will increase their inventories in the next few years, and the impact of the epidemic may make them rethink the optimal inventory problem; The electronics and communications industry may then accelerate the relocation of parts of its supply chain overseas.

But the wholesale shift that has been feared at home will not be easy.

An expert from the Market Research Center stressed to the reporter from CAIJING that the industrial chain, supply chain, service chain and value chain systems formed around the industrial chain in China are complete, and the entire service supporting capacity as well as the upstream and downstream relations are complete, after decades of cross-border market cooperation formed, at present, most of the manufacturing industry cluster is still in China.

"despite the impact of this outbreak, China's position in the global supply chain will remain strong. Industry, supply and service chains are costly to move and will not move as quickly,"the experts added, countries such as India and Vietnam, which have recently been the hot transfer points, still lack the infrastructure, labor force and policy support.

Zero Chou, who is familiar with Southeast Asia as a whole, agrees that, despite the desire of European and American clients to spread risk, Southeast Asian countries can not immediately take orders, either in terms of infrastructure, numbers of workers, or technology, the world's reliance on Chinese manufacturing can not be replaced in the short term, "so long as this challenge is overcome, the demand is there" .

He Xiang, head of Cox Pacific Consulting, told Caijing that China's 30-year-old supply chain can not be completely replaced in the short term, and some national and corporate leaders may be overly alarmed, "there is not enough reason for people to panic like this. I believe it will have some short-term impact on the supply chain, some orders will be delayed or re-planned, and there will likely be shortages, but I don't think this new coronavirus outbreak will have a measurable long-term impact on the supply chain.".

Chinese companies that have survived nearly two years of a trade war with the United States will not give up on China after more than a month of outbreaks. In recent years, the transfer of the industrial chain is basically transferred, leaving the industrial chain is not easily replaced.

This article first appeared in the March 2,2020 issue of CAIJING magazine
